fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Upon hearing the news, Miller walked 70 miles to plead with </div><div class="t m5e x15 h16 y900 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Washington for Wittman&apos;s life. </div><div class="t m5c4 x39 h16 y623 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&quot;No!&quot; Washington insisted. &quot;I cannot pardon your friend.&quot; </div><div class="t m89 x46 h16 y901 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&quot;My </div><div class="t m379 x4f h16 y901 ff7 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">friend!&quot; </div><div class="t m295 x93 h16 y624 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">exclaimed Miller. &quot;He&apos;s my worst </div><div class="t m5ac xb1 h16 y901 ff7 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">enemy!&quot; </div><div class="t m63e x46 h16 y902 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&quot;You&apos;ve just walked 70 miles to plead for the life of an enemy?&quot; </div><div class="t m37e x15 h16 y626 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Washington cried. He was so impressed by Miller&apos;s gesture that he </div><div class="t m63f x15 h16 y627 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">granted the pardon. Later, Miller took Wittman back home—no longer </div><div class="t m327 x15 h16 y628 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">a foe, but a friend.—Adapted from </div><div class="t m1fb x73 h16 y628 ff7 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Larson, Illustrations for Preaching </div><div class="t m212 x15 h16 y629 ff7 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">and Teaching, </div><div class="t m347 x56 h16 y62a ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">p. 142. </div><div class="t m214 x39 h16 y903 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In Luke 10, Jesus tells a similar story. As you study Jesus&apos; answer, </div><div class="t m5a9 x15 h16 y904 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">ask the Holy Spirit to help you determine which character in the story </div><div class="t m137 x15 h16 y905 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">you most resemble. </div><div class="t m640 x15 h16 y906 ff3 fsf fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">72 </div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.000000,0.000000,0.000000,1.000000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
